Gain Mismatch systematics¶

Goal of these studies¶

We study the systematics effects induced by gain mismatches for Litebird scanning strategy and a fake focal plane with just 2 detector pairs (to save computation time and memory at NERSC).

We inject gain drifts only in one of the two detectors as random Gaussian fluctations around 0 and with a 5% width during 1 precession period. We then apply the gain estimates (and correct for it the TODs) by regressing the signal from each detector with a template, dipole.

We correct for the noise bias as described here . According to the above entry the biased coefficient $\hat{g}$ is related to the true one $g$ by:

$ \hat{g} = g \frac{1}{1+ \sigma_{uncorr} ^2/\sigma_{corr}^2 }$

where $g$ is the slope parameter obtained by regressing of TOD of detector $i$, $d_{t,i}$ and the signal only template $s_t$, $\sigma_{uncorr}$ is the variance of uncorrelated component, defined as $\sigma^2_{uncorr}= Var(d_t -s_t)/2$, and $\sigma_{corr}$, is the variance of correlated component $\sigma^2_{corr}= Var(d_t) -\sigma^2_{uncorr} $

The whole systematics pipeline is within the TOAST framework.

Simulation Settings¶

  • simulate 1 yr of observations with LB scanning strategy parameters, $\alpha= 50$, $\beta =45$, $spinrate=0.1 rpm $, $precperiod=96.5 min$
  • Focal plane encodes 4 detectors (two det. pairs) at 140 GHz , FWHM= 25 arcmin, NET= 38.6 $\mu K \sqrt{s}$, sample rate= 40 Hz
  • not spinning HWP /!\
  • $f_{knee}$ is allowed to range 0,20, 50 mHz
  • Input signal : CMB T only map + Dipole + Noise
  • Output maps : destriped with MADAM (baseline=1min, noisefilter=Off)

Let's have a look of the hitmaps..

Temperature map encodes = Dipole + CMB T. Polariz. maps are essentially null

we now inject gain drifts to signal only observations¶

We look at residual maps, i.e.
$ \Delta m = m_{out} - m_{in} $

We get non null signal to Q, and U maps, that's the expected T-> P leakage from gain drifts.

We thus estimate the gains and apply the correction at the TOD level, as depicted above

You may notice that residual Q and U maps are a factor ~10 times smaller than the ones w/o any gain correction (see above ).

We then compute full sky power spectra (with anafast) from the residual maps, $\Delta m$.

Recall that no noise has been coadded to the TODs so far, so that the plots above represent the level of accuracy our estimator might achieve.

Pros: By comparing the blue with the orange solid lines should highlights the effects of gain correction. As expected they are small for the temperature maps, but in terms of EE and BB power the correction is very effective: it may correct the T->P leakage as much as 3 orders of magnitude.

Cons: there is a lot of power at $\ell<10$ scales.
